  <p class="page-desc">{ws.description}</p>

  <div class="worksheet-box">
    <div class="config-panel">
      <h3>Settings</h3>
      <div class="config-inputs">
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgProblems">Number of Problems</label>
          <input type="number" id="cfgProblems" value="20" min="5" max="40" />
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgRoundTo">Round To</label>
          <select id="cfgRoundTo">
            <option value="10">Nearest 10</option>
            <option value="100">Nearest 100</option>
            <option value="1000">Nearest 1,000</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgMaxNumber">Max Number</label>
          <select id="cfgMaxNumber">
            <option value="99">Up to 99</option>
            <option value="999" selected>Up to 999</option>
            <option value="9999">Up to 9,999</option>
            <option value="99999">Up to 99,999</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-actions">
      <button class="ws-btn primary" id="btnGenerate">Generate New</button>
      <button class="ws-btn print" id="btnPrint">Print</button>
      <label class="toggle-label">
        <input type="checkbox" id="toggleAnswers" />
        Show Answers
      </label>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-content" id="worksheetContent">
      <div class="worksheet-header-print">
        <h2>Rounding Practice</h2>
        <div class="name-date">
          <span>Name: ___________________</span>
          <span>Date: ___________________</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-grid" id="problemGrid"></div>
      <div class="answer-key hidden" id="answerKey">
        <h3>Answer Key</h3>
        <div class="answer-grid" id="answerGrid"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>Why Rounding Is Important</h2>
    <p>Rounding is a fundamental math skill that helps students estimate and work with numbers more efficiently. When we round a number, we replace it with a nearby number that is easier to work with mentally. For example, rounding 487 to the nearest hundred gives us 500, which is much simpler to use in mental calculations. Rounding is used constantly in everyday life, from estimating the total cost of groceries to understanding statistics and measurements reported in the news.</p>
    <p>These free printable rounding worksheets provide unlimited practice with rounding numbers to the nearest 10, 100, and 1,000. Every worksheet is randomly generated, so students always have fresh problems to work with. The configurable settings let you tailor the difficulty to each student's level.</p>

    <h2>How to Round Numbers</h2>
    <p>The standard rounding rule is simple: look at the digit immediately to the right of the place you are rounding to. If that digit is 5 or greater, round up. If it is 4 or less, round down.</p>
    <h3>Rounding to the Nearest 10</h3>
    <p>Look at the ones digit. If it is 0, 1, 2, 3, or 4, round down (keep the tens digit the same). If it is 5, 6, 7, 8, or 9, round up (increase the tens digit by 1). Examples: 43 rounds to 40, 67 rounds to 70, 85 rounds to 90, and 120 rounds to 120.</p>

    <h3>Rounding to the Nearest 100</h3>
    <p>Look at the tens digit. If it is 0, 1, 2, 3, or 4, round down. If it is 5, 6, 7, 8, or 9, round up. Examples: 234 rounds to 200, 678 rounds to 700, and 1,450 rounds to 1,500.</p>

    <h3>Rounding to the Nearest 1,000</h3>
    <p>Look at the hundreds digit and apply the same rule. Examples: 2,345 rounds to 2,000, 7,891 rounds to 8,000, and 14,500 rounds to 15,000.</p>

    <h2>Grade-Level Guide for Rounding</h2>
    <h3>Third Grade (Ages 8-9)</h3>
    <p>Third graders begin learning to round numbers. Start with rounding two-digit numbers to the nearest 10, which is the simplest application of the rounding rule. Use the "Up to 99" max number setting with "Nearest 10" to create appropriate worksheets. Once comfortable, extend to three-digit numbers rounded to the nearest 10 and 100.</p>

    <h3>Fourth Grade (Ages 9-10)</h3>
    <p>Fourth graders practice rounding numbers up to 9,999 to any place value. They use rounding to estimate sums and differences. Use the "Up to 9,999" setting and alternate between rounding to the nearest 10, 100, and 1,000 to provide varied practice.</p>

    <h3>Fifth Grade (Ages 10-11)</h3>
    <p>Fifth graders round larger numbers and apply rounding in problem-solving contexts. They understand that rounding is a tool for estimation and can choose the appropriate level of rounding for different situations. Use the "Up to 99,999" setting for challenging practice.</p>

    <h2>Tips for Teaching Rounding</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Use a number line.</strong> Drawing a number line and marking the two nearest multiples helps students visualize which direction to round. For example, when rounding 67 to the nearest 10, mark 60 and 70 and show that 67 is closer to 70.</li>
      <li><strong>Teach the "5 or more" rule clearly.</strong> Many students struggle with numbers that have 5 in the deciding position. Emphasize that 5 always rounds up in standard rounding.</li>
      <li><strong>Connect to estimation.</strong> Show students how rounding helps them check their arithmetic. "Is 389 + 412 about 800? Let me round: 400 + 400 = 800. Yes, that makes sense."</li>
      <li><strong>Practice with real-world contexts.</strong> Population figures, distances, and prices all provide natural rounding practice. "The city has a population of 47,832. What is that rounded to the nearest thousand?"</li>
      <li><strong>Watch for common errors.</strong> Some students round all digits instead of just changing the rounding place and setting everything after it to zero. Others confuse which digit to look at when deciding whether to round up or down.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to Use These Rounding Worksheets</h2>
    <p>Choose the number of problems, what place to round to, and the maximum number size using the settings above. Click "Generate New" for a fresh worksheet. Use "Print" for a clean printable page and "Show Answers" to check work. New problems are generated with every click, providing unlimited practice.</p>

    <h2>Related Worksheets</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/place-value-worksheets/">Place Value Worksheets</a> - Understand digit values, expanded form, and standard form.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/comparing-numbers-worksheets/">Comparing Numbers Worksheets</a> - Practice using &gt;, &lt;, and = symbols.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/addition-worksheets/">Addition Worksheets</a> - Multi-digit addition practice.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/subtraction-worksheets/">Subtraction Worksheets</a> - Multi-digit subtraction practice.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-bottom" format="horizontal" />
</BaseLayout>

<script is:inline>
  var problems = [];

  function randInt(min, max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
  }

  function formatNumber(n) {
    return n.toLocaleString('en-US');
  }

  function roundTo(n, place) {
    return Math.round(n / place) * place;
  }

  function generateProblems() {
    var count = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgProblems').value, 10);
    var roundPlace = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgRoundTo').value, 10);
    var maxNum = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgMaxNumber').value, 10);

    if (isNaN(count) || count < 5) count = 5;
    if (count > 40) count = 40;

    // Ensure maxNum is large enough for the rounding place
    var minNum = roundPlace;
    if (minNum > maxNum) minNum = Math.max(1, Math.floor(maxNum / 10));

    problems = [];
    for (var i = 0; i < count; i++) {
      var n = randInt(minNum, maxNum);
      // Avoid numbers already perfectly rounded (they are trivial)
      if (n % roundPlace === 0 && maxNum > roundPlace * 2) {
        n += randInt(1, roundPlace - 1);
        if (n > maxNum) n = maxNum - randInt(1, roundPlace - 1);
        if (n < minNum) n = minNum + randInt(1, roundPlace - 1);
      }
      var answer = roundTo(n, roundPlace);
      problems.push({ number: n, answer: answer });
    }

    renderProblems();
    renderAnswerKey();
    updateAnswerVisibility();
  }

  function renderProblems() {
    var grid = document.getElementById('problemGrid');
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var roundPlace = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgRoundTo').value, 10);
    var placeLabel = roundPlace === 10 ? 'ten' : roundPlace === 100 ? 'hundred' : 'thousand';
    var html = '';

    for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
      var p = problems[i];
      html += '<div class="problem">';
      html += '<div class="problem-number">' + (i + 1) + ')</div>';
      html += '<div class="problem-text">Round ' + formatNumber(p.number) + ' to the nearest ' + placeLabel + '.</div>';
      html += '<div class="problem-answer' + (showAnswers ? ' revealed' : '') + '">';
      html += showAnswers ? formatNumber(p.answer) : '___________';
      html += '</div>';
      html += '</div>';
    }

    grid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function renderAnswerKey() {
    var answerGrid = document.getElementById('answerGrid');
    var html = '';
    for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
      html += '<div class="answer-item">';
      html += '<span class="q">' + (i + 1) + '.</span>';
      html += '<span class="a">' + formatNumber(problems[i].answer) + '</span>';
      html += '</div>';
    }
    answerGrid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function updateAnswerVisibility() {
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var answerKey = document.getElementById('answerKey');
    if (showAnswers) { answerKey.classList.remove('hidden'); }
    else { answerKey.classList.add('hidden'); }
    renderProblems();
  }

  document.getElementById('btnGenerate').addEventListener('click', generateProblems);
  document.getElementById('btnPrint').addEventListener('click', function () { window.print(); });
  document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').addEventListener('change', updateAnswerVisibility);
  generateProblems();
</script>
